---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import ProductCard from '../components/ProductCard.astro';
import products from '../../data/products.json';

import AffiliateDisclosure from '../components/AffiliateDisclosure.astro';

const mics = products.filter(p => p.category === 'microphone');
const at2020 = mics.find(p => p.id === 'audio-technica-at2020')!;
const yeti = mics.find(p => p.id === 'blue-yeti')!;
const q2u = mics.find(p => p.id === 'samson-q2u')!;
---

<Layout
  title="Best Microphones Under $100 (2026) — HomeRecordingGear"
  description="The 3 best microphones under $100 for home recording and podcasting. Honest picks for beginners, no fluff."
>
  <article class="space-y-8">
    <header class="space-y-3">
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wide font-medium">Best-of list</p>
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Best Microphones Under $100 (2026)</h1>
      <p class="text-gray-600 text-lg">
        Three mics worth buying. One clear winner for most people. Skip everything else.
      </p>
    </header>

    <AffiliateDisclosure />

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-xl p-5 space-y-1">
      <p class="font-semibold text-gray-900">Bottom line up front</p>
      <p class="text-gray-700">
        If you record vocals or podcast with a decent recording space, get the
        <strong>Audio-Technica AT2020</strong>. It's the best condenser mic at this price.
        If you want plug-and-play USB with no interface needed, get the <strong>Blue Yeti</strong>.
        On a tight budget, the <strong>Samson Q2U</strong> is the smartest buy — XLR and USB in one mic.
      </p>
    </div>

    <section class="space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Our picks</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <ProductCard
          name={at2020.name}
          price={at2020.price}
          rating={at2020.rating}
          reviewCount={at2020.review_count}
          retailers={at2020.retailers}
          badge="Best overall"
          description="Best-in-class condenser at this price. Needs an audio interface with XLR."
        />
        <ProductCard
          name={yeti.name}
          price={yeti.price}
          rating={yeti.rating}
          reviewCount={yeti.review_count}
          retailers={yeti.retailers}
          badge="Best USB"
          description="Plug-and-play USB. No interface needed. Great for podcasters and streamers."
        />
        <ProductCard
          name={q2u.name}
          price={q2u.price}
          rating={q2u.rating}
          reviewCount={q2u.review_count}
          retailers={q2u.retailers}
          badge="Best budget"
          description="Both USB and XLR outputs. Grow into an interface later without buying a new mic."
        />
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-3 text-gray-700">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900">How we chose</h2>
      <p>
        Under $100 is a crowded category with a lot of junk. I narrowed it to mics with
        a proven track record, consistent quality control, and genuinely good sound — not
        just good specs on paper. These three show up in professional studios and home setups alike.
      </p>
      <p>
        I excluded USB condensers that sound thin on voice, dynamic mics that need a loud preamp
        to shine, and anything with flaky build quality at this price.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900">What beginners actually ask before buying</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500">Questions pulled from r/homerecording and Sweetwater's Q&A — these come up constantly.</p>
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <div class="border-l-4 border-gray-200 pl-4 space-y-1">
          <p class="font-medium text-gray-900">"Is the AT2020 too sensitive for a noisy apartment?"</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 text-sm">Yes, if your room has a lot of echo or street noise bleeding in. Condenser mics pick up everything. In that case the Samson Q2U (dynamic) is more forgiving — it focuses on what's directly in front of it and rejects room noise better.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="border-l-4 border-gray-200 pl-4 space-y-1">
          <p class="font-medium text-gray-900">"Why does the Blue Yeti sound echoey in recordings?"</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 text-sm">Almost always because the cardioid pattern is set wrong or the mic is too far from your mouth. The Yeti needs to be 4–6 inches from you, not across the desk. This is the #1 complaint and it's a placement issue, not a mic quality issue.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="border-l-4 border-gray-200 pl-4 space-y-1">
          <p class="font-medium text-gray-900">"Do I need a pop filter?"</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 text-sm">For vocals, yes — a $10 pop filter prevents the plosive bursts ("p" and "b" sounds) that are annoying to edit out later. Not strictly necessary for spoken-word podcasting if you speak across the mic rather than directly into it.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-3 text-gray-700">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Do you need an audio interface?</h2>
      <p>
        The AT2020 is XLR-only, so yes — you'll need an interface. The Focusrite Scarlett Solo
        is the standard rec for beginners and adds ~$120. The Blue Yeti and Samson Q2U both
        connect directly over USB with no interface needed.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href="/what-audio-interface-do-i-need" class="text-blue-600 hover:underline">
          Read: What audio interface do I actually need? →
        </a>
      </p>
    </section>
  </article>
</Layout>
